    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-04-03T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-04-03T08:00:00-05:00" n="857"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d857">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">640.0031/107: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-04-03T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 3, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 3—12:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>141. During the course of my conversation [with] Ciano<note n="9"
                        xml:id="d857fn9">Count Galeazzo Ciano, Italian Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> yesterday I reminded him of Secretary Hull’s conviction that
                    the only way to bring the world out of the present international chaos and
                    misunderstanding was through economic recovery but that the United States could
                    not carry the whole load in this respect and that we were therefore doing our
                    utmost to persuade other governments to adopt programs to this end. I suggested
                    that if Ciano and other Italian leaders would associate Italy in the cause of
                    economic recovery and get away from the idea of the use of “force” there would
                    be an instant and friendly response not only throughout the United States but
                    elsewhere.</p>
                <p>Ciano replied that he welcomed this suggestion, that he was planning to make a
                    speech on international affairs in the Chamber in the <pb facs="0844" n="832"
                        xml:id="pg_832"/> course of 3 weeks or a month, and that he would devote a
                    substantial part of it to international economic recovery.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
